<h1 align="center"><a name="visual-tables">Tables</a></h1>
<h2>Introduction to tables</h2>

<p>Tables represent relationships between data. Authors specify these
relationships in the <a href="conform.html#doclanguage">document
language</a> and specify their
<em>presentation</em> in CSS, in two ways: visually and aurally.

<P>Authors may specify the visual rendering of a table as a
rectangular grid of cells. Rows and columns of cells may be organized
into row groups and column groups. Rows, columns, row groups, row
columns, and cells may have borders drawn around them (there are two
border models in CSS2). Authors may align data vertically or
horizontally within a cell and align data in all cells of a row or
column.

<P>Authors may also specify the aural rendering of a table; how
headers and data will be spoken. In the document language, authors may
label cells and groups of cells so that when rendered aurally, cell
headers are spoken before cell data. In effect, this "serializes" the
table: users browsing the table aurally hear a sequence of headers
followed by data.

<div class="example"><P>
Here is a simple three-row, three-column 
table described in HTML 4.0:

<PRE class="html-example">
&lt;TABLE&gt;
&lt;CAPTION&gt;This is a simple 3x3 table&lt;/CAPTION&gt;
&lt;TR id="row1"&gt;
   &lt;TH&gt;Header 1      &lt;TH&gt;Header 2      &lt;TH&gt;Header 3
&lt;TR id="row2"&gt;
   &lt;TD&gt;Cell 1        &lt;TD&gt;Cell 2        &lt;TD&gt;Cell 3
&lt;TR id="row3"&gt;
   &lt;TD&gt;Cell 4        &lt;TD&gt;Cell 5        &lt;TD&gt;Cell 6
&lt;/TABLE&gt;
</PRE>

<P>This code creates one table (the TABLE element), three
rows (the TR elements), three header cells (the TH elements),
and six data cells (the TD elements). Note that the three columns
of this example are specified implicitly: there are as many
columns in the table as required by header and data cells.

<P>The following CSS rule centers the text horizontally
in the header cells and present the data with a bold font weight:</P>

<PRE>
   TH { text-align: center; font-weight: bold }
</PRE>

<P>The next rules align the text of the three header cells 
along a common baseline and centers the text in each data cell:</p>


<PRE>
   TH { vertical-align: baseline }
   TD { vertical-align: center }
</PRE>

<P>The next rules specify that the row of header cells will be surrounded
by a 3px solid blue border and each row of data cells will be surrounded
by a 1px solid black border:</P>

<PRE>
   TABLE { cell-spacing: none }
   TR#row1 { border-top: 3px solid blue }
   TR#row2 { border-top: 1px solid black }
   TR#row3 { border-top: 1px solid black }
</PRE>

<P>Note, however, that the borders around the rows overlap where the
rows meet. What color (black or blue) and thickness (1px or 3px) will
the border between row1 and row2 be? We discuss this in the section on
<a href="#border-conflict-resolution">border conflict resolution.</a>

<P>The following rule positions the table caption centered, above
the table:</P>

<PRE>
   CAPTION { caption-side: top }
</PRE>

<P>Finally, the following rule specifies that, when rendered
aurally, each column of data is to be spoken 
as a "Header, Data, Data":</P>

<PRE>
   TH { speak-header: once }
</PRE>

<P>For instance, the first column would be spoken "Header1 Cell1 Cell4".
The following rule:</p>

<PRE>
   TH { speak-header: always }
</PRE>

<P>would be spoken "Header1 Cell1 Header1 Cell4". 
</div>

<P>The preceding example shows how CSS works with HTML 4.0 elements;
in HTML 4.0, the semantics of the various table elements (TABLE,
CAPTION, THEAD, TBODY, TFOOT, COL, COLGROUP, TH, and TD) are
well-defined. In other document languages (such as XML), there may not
be pre-defined table elements. Therefore, CSS2 allows authors to "map"
document language elements to table elements via the <span
class="propinst-display">'display'</span> property. For example, the
following rule makes the FOO element act like an HTML TABLE element
and the BAR element act like a CAPTION element:</p>

<PRE class="example">
   FOO { display : table }
   BAR { display : table-caption }
</PRE>

<P>We discuss the various table elements in the following section. In
this specification, the term <span class="index-def" title="table
element"><dfn>table element</dfn></span> refers to any element
involved in the creation of a table. An "internal" table element is
one that produces a row, row group, column, column group, or cell.

<H2>The CSS table model</h2>

<P>The CSS table model is based on the HTML 4.0 table model, in which
the structure of a table closely parallels the visual layout of the
table. In this model, a table consists of an optional caption and any
number of rows of cells. The table model is said to be "row primary"
since authors specify rows, not columns, explicitly in the document
language. Columns are derived once all the rows have been specified --
the first cell of each row belongs to the first column, the second to
the second column, etc.). Rows and columns may be grouped structurally
and this grouping reflected in presentation (e.g., a border may
be drawn around a group of rows).

<P>Thus, the table model consists of tables, captions, 
rows, row groups, columns, column groups, and cells. 

<P>The CSS model does not require that the <a
href="conform.html#doclanguage">document language</a> include elements
that correspond to each of these components.  For document
languages (such as XML) that do not have pre-defined table elements,
authors must map document language elements to table elements; this is
done with the <span class="propinst-display">'display'</span>
property. The following <span
class="propinst-display">'display'</span> values assign table
semantics to an arbitrary element:</p>

<dl>
<dt><strong>table</strong> (In HTML: TABLE)
<dd>Specifies that an element defines a <a
href="visuren.html#block-level">block-level</a> table: it
is a rectangular block that participates
in a <a href="visuren.html#block-formatting">block formatting
context</a>.

<dt><strong>inline-table</strong> (In HTML: TABLE)
<dd>Specifies that an element defines an 
<a href="visuren.html#inline">inline-level</a> table: it
is a rectangular block that participates 
in an <a href="visuren.html#inline-formatting">inline formatting
context</a>).

<dt><strong>table-row</strong> (In HTML: TR)
<dd>Specifies that an element refers to a row of cells.
Note, however, that the calculation of <em>which</em> row of
cells depends on the document language.

<dt><strong>table-row-group</strong> (In HTML: TBODY)
<dd>Specifies that an element groups one or more rows.

<dt><strong>table-header-group</strong> (In HTML: THEAD)
<dd>Like 'table-row-group', but for visual rendering,
the row group is always displayed 
before all other rows and rowgroups and after any top
captions. 

<dt><strong>table-footer-group</strong> (In HTML: TFOOT)
<dd>Like 'table-row-group', but for visual rendering,
the row group is always displayed 
after all other rows and rowgroups and before any bottom
captions. 

<dt><strong>table-column</strong> (In HTML: COL)
<dd>Specifies that an element refers to a column
of cells. Note, however, that the calculation of <em>which</em> column 
of cells depends on the document language.

<dt><strong>table-column-group</strong> (In HTML: COLGROUP)
<dd>Specifies that an element groups one or more columns.

<dt><strong>table-cell</strong> (In HTML: TD, TH)
<dd>Specifies that an element contains table cell
data. 'Table-cell' elements may only be inside of 
'table-row' elements.

<dt><strong>table-caption</strong> (In HTML: CAPTION)
<dd>Specifies a caption for the table. Inherited
values of properties set for a caption element come
from the parent table element (e.g., percentage widths).
</dl>

<p>The <a href="sample.html">default style sheet for HTML 4.0</a>
in the appendix illustrates the use of these values for HTML 4.0:</p>

<pre class="example">
TABLE    { display: table }
TR       { display: table-row }
THEAD    { display: table-header-group }
TBODY    { display: table-footer-group }
TFOOT    { display: table-row-group }
COL      { display: table-column }
COLGROUP { display: table-column-group }
TD, TH   { display: table-cell }
CAPTION  { display: table-caption }
</pre>

<div class="note"><P> <em><strong>Note.</strong> User agents should <a
href="syndata.html#skip">skip</a> these <span
class="propinst-display">'display'</span> property values
for HTML documents, since authors should not alter an element's
expected behavior.</em>
</div>

<h3>Anonymous table elements</h3>

<P>For document languages other than HTML 4.0, authors may designate
elements to be some, but not all, of the table elements in the CSS2
table model. In such a case, the "missing" elements are inserted as <a
href="visuren.html#anonymous">anonymous elements</a> according
to the following rules:</p>

<ol>
<li>Any table element will automatically generate a whole table tree
around itself, consisting of at least a 'table'/'inline-table', a
'table-row', and a 'table-cell'.
<li>If the parent a 'table-cell' is not a 'table-row',
an anonymous 'table-row' element will be assumed as its parent, and
this anonymous element will span all consecutive 'table-cell'
siblings. 
<li>If the parent of a 'table-row' is not a
'table'/'inline-table' nor a row group element, an anonymous 'table'
will be assumed as its parent, spanning all consecutive siblings that
also need an anonymous 'table' parent.
</ol>

<P>The same holds for row group elements.

<div class="example">
<p>In this XML example, an anonymous 'table' is inserted to
contain the HBOX element:</p>

<pre class="xml-example">
&lt;HBOX&gt;
  &lt;VBOX&gt;George&lt;/VBOX&gt;
  &lt;VBOX&gt;4287&lt;/VBOX&gt;
  &lt;VBOX&gt;1998&lt;/VBOX&gt;
&lt;/HBOX&gt;
</pre>

<p>The style sheet is:</p>

<pre class="example">
HBOX {display: table-row}
VBOX {display: table-cell}
</pre>
</div><!-- end of example -->

<p>Anonymous 'table-cell' elements are inserted as children of
'table-rows', to contain consecutive children that are not
'table-cell' elements.</p>

<div class="example">
<p>In this example, three anonymous 'table-cell' elements are inserted
to contain the text in the ROWs. Note that the text is further
encapsulated in anonymous inline boxes, as explained in <a
href="visuren.html#anonymous">visual rendering model</a>:</p>

<pre class="xml-example">
&lt;STACK&gt;
  &lt;ROW&gt;This is the &lt;D&gt;top&lt;/D&gt; row.&lt;/ROW&gt;
  &lt;ROW&gt;This is the &lt;D&gt;middle&lt;/D&gt; row.&lt;/ROW&gt;
  &lt;ROW&gt;This is the &lt;D&gt;bottom&lt;/D&gt; row.&lt;/ROW&gt;
&lt;/STACK&gt;
</pre>

<p>The style sheet is:</p>

<pre class="example">
STACK {display: inline-table}
ROW {display: table-row}
D {display: inline; font-weight: bolder}
</pre>

</div><!-- end of example -->

<p>Elements with <span class="propinst-display">'display'</span> set
to 'table-column' or 'table-column-group' are not rendered (exactly as
if they had 'display: none'), but they are useful, because they may
have attributes which induce a certain style for the columns they
represent.</p>

<h2>Table selectors</h2>

<p>Due to the uniqueness of the table structure, there are several
additional semantics and pseudo-classes for table elements.</p>

<div class="note"><p>
<em><strong>Note.</strong>
The implementation cost of these features may be high. They require two
passes over the style sheet: first to determine the <span
class="propinst-display">'display'</span>, <span
class="propinst-float">'float'</span> and <span
class="propinst-position">'position'</span> properties using the
normal element hierarchy, than again searching for selectors that
match cell element inside column elements. In the second kind of
rules, <span class="propinst-display">'display'</span>, <span
class="propinst-position">'position'</span> and <span
class="propinst-float">'float'</span> may not appear.
</em>
</div>

<h3>Column and cell selectors</h3>

<p>Table cell selectors -- unlike other selectors in CSS -- may belong
to two contexts: rows and columns.  An author may write a CSS rule
that applies to either of the two contexts, but not to both (i.e.,
the contexts do not interact).

<P>Thus, to specify the color of all the cells in a particular
row, one would write:</P>

<pre class="example">
   TR.row1 TD { color: red }   /* HTML row and data cell */
</pre>

<P>To specify the color of all the cells in a particular
column, one would write:</P>

<pre class="example">
   COL.col3 TD { color: blue }   /* HTML column and data cell */
</pre>

<P>The following rule <em>does not</em> specify the color
of a single cell at the intersection of a particular row
and column:</p>

<pre class="example">
   TR.row1 COL.col3 TD { color: green }   /* This doesn't work!*/
</pre>

<P>Though syntactically correct, this rule neglects the fact
that row and column contexts do not mix. To specify properties
for a cell in a particular row and column authors may use
an "id" selector, as in:</p>

<pre class="example">
   TD.one-cell { color: green }   /* HTML row and data cell */
</pre>

<!-- I added row to this note. -IJ -->
<div class="note"><P>
<em><strong>Note.</strong>
If a cell spans more than one row or column, all
row or column parents apply in the selector.
</em>
</div>

<h3>Row pseudo-classes</h3>

<!-- Need intro -IJ -->

<p class="note">[The implementation cost of this feature is probably
even higher than the one in the previous section. Not only does it
require two passes, it also precludes the use of hash tables for quick
access to rules.]</p>

<dl>
<dt><strong>:row[n], :row[%n], :row[%n+m]</strong>
<dd>This pseudo-class allows
the author to specify "the third row" (":row[3]"), "every third row"
(":row[%3]"), or "every third row, starting with the second row"
(":row[%3 + 1") (rows are zero-indexed).

<dt><strong>:row-even</strong>
<dd>This is a shortcut for a pseudo-class of
":row[%2]".

<dt><strong>:row-odd</strong>
<dd>This is a shortcut for a pseudo-class of
":row[%2+1.
</dl>

<!-- Need example  -IJ -->

<h3>Column pseudo-classes</h3>

<!-- Need intro -IJ -->

<dl>
<dt><strong>:column[n], :column[%n], :column[%n+m]</strong>
<dd>This pseudo-class
allows the author to specify (for example) "the third column"
(":column[3]"), "every third column" (":column[%3]"), or "every third
column, starting with the second column" (":column[%3 + 1") (columns
are zero-indexed).

<dt><strong>:column-even</strong>
<dd>This is a shortcut for a pseudo-class of
":column[%2]".

<dt><strong>:column-odd</strong>
<dd>This is a shortcut for a pseudo-class of
":column[%2+1]".
</dl>

